\begin_layout Chapter
A CONTINUUM MODEL OF THE ADSORPTION OF HARD SPHERES
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Computational methods have been applied to model and predict protein adsorption,
 but their success has been limited due to the complexity of the problem.
 While nanoscale simulation methods like molecular dynamics (MD) have the
 potential to predict protein adsorption from first principles, the small
 (femtosecond) time step required by atomistic techniques presents a significant
 obstacle.
 The adsorption of proteins and their subsequent rearrangement occurs on
 a time scale of seconds to hours 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Latour2005"

\end_inset

.
 , while it was recently reported that an advanced MD simulation on a specially
 designed supercomputer has the ability to simulate several microseconds
 of protein behavior 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dror2010"

\end_inset

.
 MD has been used to simulate the adsorption of a fragment of fibrinogen
 with explicit solvent molecules for 5ns of simulated time 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Agashe2005"

\end_inset

.
 A similar study was carried out to model the interaction between lysozyme
 and a graphite surface for 500ps 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Raffaini2010"

\end_inset

.
 It was recently reported that an advanced MD simulation on a specially
 designed supercomputer has the ability to simulate several microseconds
 of protein behavior 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dror2010"

\end_inset

.
 Because of the limitations of atomistic models, simplified models are widely
 used to model protein adsorption.
 Colloidal models represent a protein molecule with a simplified geometric
 shape (typically a sphere or ellipsoid) and interactions are modeled by
 DLVO (electrostatic and van der Walls) forces
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "evans1994colloidal,Roth1993,Lenhoff1995"

\end_inset

.
 Recently, Brownian dynamics simulations been used to implement colloidal-scale
 simulations of protein transport and adsorption 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Unni2005,Magan2006,Quinn2008"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A fundamental limitation of nanoscale and mesoscale simulation methods is
 that they are impractical for modeling transport in practical applications
 such as medical implants, engineered tissue constructs, blood flow simulations,
 and microfluidic devices.
 Computational fluid dynamics (CFD) simulations are widely used to model
 transport in macroscale systems.
 Simplified continuum models of adsorption based upon chemical kinetics
 have been used as adsorbing boundary conditions in CFD simulations
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Jenkins2004,Glaser1993,Edwards1999"

\end_inset

.
 At first, kinetic models of adsorption were formulated based upon the assumptio
ns of the Langmuir adsorption model 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Andrade1986"

\end_inset

.
 More recently random sequential adsorption (RSA) models have been applied
 to characterize the blocking of the surface more rigorously for various
 particle shapes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Talbot2000287"

\end_inset

.
 The available surface for adsorption is usually quantified through the
 available surface function 
\begin_inset Formula $ASF\left(\theta\right)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is the fraction of surface that is covered by adsorbed particles.
 Many types of kinetic models are currently used to model protein adsorption
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Rabe2010"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Continuum models can be linked to discrete-particle simulations using the
 principles of chemical thermodynamics.
 The available surface function has been generalized to depend on the height
 above the adsorbing surface as well as the fractional surface coverage
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Adamczyk1999"

\end_inset

.
 Adsorbed particles create an energy barrier which becomes higher as the
 number of adsorbed particles increases, reducing the flux of particles
 to the surface.
 This barrier incorporates steric exclusion due to the blocking effect of
 hard particles and the longer-ranged repulsive effect of electrostatic
 interactions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Adamczyk2000"

\end_inset

.
 This model has been implemented by making simplifying assumptions about
 transport to the surface.
 For example, the surface boundary layer approximation (SFBLA) assumes that
 the interface is one-dimensional and the flux through the boundary layer
 is independent of the position above the surface 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Adamczyk1999a"

\end_inset

.
 Transport to the interface has been accounted for by coupling the adsorption
 model to a diffusive transport model, but the kinetic coefficients of the
 adsorption model were approximated with results from an RSA model 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Adamczyk2000"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To fully account for the blocking effect of hard spheres, it cannot be assumed
 that the flux at the surface 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{s}$
\end_inset

 is equal to the flux at the interface with the continuum 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{c}$
\end_inset

 .
 A particle may diffuse into the boundary region, collide with adsorbed
 particles, and diffuse back out of the boundary region at a later time.
 At any instant, the flux at the surface will be less than or equal to the
 flux at the bulk interface.
 Brownian dynamics simulations of hard sphere adsorption were utilized to
 obtain configurations of adsorbed spheres, which were then analyzed to
 obtain the generalized blocking function 
\begin_inset Formula $AVF\left(h,\theta\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The principles of non-equilibrium thermodynamics were used to derive a
 continuum model of hard-sphere adsorption in which the flux of particles
 was allowed to vary with the distance from the surface.
 The generalized blocking function from the Brownian dynamics simulations
 was used to determine the coefficients of the continuum model, which was
 solved numerically in the region near the surface.
 This model was used as a boundary condition for a conventional CFD simulation
 to predict coupled transport and adsorption.
 Good agreement was found between the kinetics obtained from the Brownian
 dynamics simulations and the kinetics predicted by the continuum model.
\end_layout

