\begin_layout Standard
The coefficients of the generalized diffusion equation are functions of
 the activity coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, which is a function of space and the number and configuration of adsorbed
 particles.
 Computation of the activity coefficient is critical to obtain a useful
 model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Brownian Dynamics Simulation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A Brownian dynamics simulation of irreversible hard-sphere adsorption was
 used to obtain configurations of adsorbed particles.
 The Langevin position equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Elimelech1998"

\end_inset

 was used to update the position of each particle at each time step: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{r}_{i}(t+\Delta t)=\mathbf{r}_{i}(t)+\mathbf{g}_{q}\sqrt{2\, D\,\Delta t}\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the position of particle 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

 is the simulation time step, 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is the diffusion coefficient, and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{q}\in\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 is a vector of random numbers drawn from a Gaussian distribution with a
 mean of zero and a variance of one.
 At each time step, all particles in the domain were moved simultaneously,
 and overlaps were detected.
 Any particle which overlapped another was reset to its original position
 and moved again using a different random vector, until each particle found
 a valid position.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simulation domain was a rectangular box with height 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and width and length 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Periodic boundary conditions were applied on the four sides of the simulation
 domain so that a particle that exited one side of the box re-entered on
 the opposite side.
 An adsorbing boundary condition was used for the bottom of the box.
 A particle adsorbed when it reached the adsorbing surface without overlapping
 any previously adsorbed particles.
 The configuration of adsorbed particles was recorded every time a new particle
 adsorbed.
 To simulate a perfect adsorbing boundary for validation purposes, adsorbed
 particles could be moved out of the simulation domain so they did not interfere
 with the adsorption of additional particles.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two different boundary conditions were used for the top of the box.
 To simulate constant near-surface concentration a reflecting boundary was
 used for the top of the box.
 At each time step, the particles in the box were counted.
 If there were too few particles in the box, particles were added at positions
 drawn from a uniform random distribution, ensuring that the newly added
 particles did not overlap with existing particles.
 If there were too many particles in the domain, a particle was chosen at
 random for deletion.
 To simulate diffusion on a semi-infinite domain, an open box top was used
 to allow the Brownian dynamics simulation to exchange particles with an
 infinite bulk solution.
 This boundary condition was implemented according to the multi-scale linking
 algorithm described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Magan2004"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

