\begin_layout Subsubsection
Controls and Validation for the Brownian dynamics simulation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Brownian dynamics simulation was validated by simulating diffusion-limited
 adsorption and comparing the results to the analytical solution of a well-known
 boundary value problem.
 A perfect adsorbing boundary condition (perfect sink) was used so that
 particles that adsorbed to the surface did not block the adsorption of
 additional particles.
 The classical diffusion equation in one dimension can be solve analytically
 with the boundary conditions 
\begin_inset Formula $n(h=0,t)=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n(h\rightarrow\infty,t)=n_{b}$
\end_inset

.
 Control simulations were performed with three different box widths (75,
 100, 150) to ensure that edge effects were not distorting the pattern of
 adsorbed particles.
 The simulation was also tested with three time steps (
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-5}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-6}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-7}sec$
\end_inset

) to determine the largest time step that would produce accurate results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Monte Carlo Calculation of the Activity Coefficient
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The activity coefficient was determined empirically from the results of
 the Brownian dynamics simulations using the Widom particle insertion method
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Widom1963,Dullens2005"

\end_inset

.
 In this method, a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

test
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 particle is introduced into a fixed configuration of particles and the
 energy of interaction 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 between the test particle and the surrounding particles is calculated.
 The activity 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 can be computed by taking the canonical average of many such insertions,
 using the formula
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{n}{a}=\left\langle \exp\left(\frac{-\psi}{k_{B}T}\right)\right\rangle \label{eq:Widom equation}\end{equation}

\end_inset

For hard spheres, the energy of interaction is either infinite if the test
 particle overlaps an existing particle or zero if it does not.
 Therefore the activity coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=a/n$
\end_inset

 is also infinite if the test particle overlaps another, and zero if it
 does not.
 To avoid dealing with infinite quantities, the available volume function
 (AVF) was defined as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
AVF\left(h,\theta\right)=\gamma^{-1}\left(h,\theta\right)\label{eq:AVF}\end{equation}

\end_inset

The AVF is the three-dimensional equivalent of the available surface function.
 The value of the AVF is one if the test particle does not overlap with
 a simulation particle and zero if it does overlap.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After the completion of an ensemble of Brownian dynamics simulations, the
 AVF was calculated for each run at multiple values of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

 a planar grid of non-overlapping test particles was constructed in the
 simulation domain at a given height 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{i}$
\end_inset

 above the adsorbing surface.
 Particles in solution with 
\begin_inset Formula $h\geq2$
\end_inset

 cannot interact with adsorbed particles, as shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Geometry"

\end_inset

.
 The position of each test particle was offset by a small random vector
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $x-y$
\end_inset

 plane and each test particle was checked for overlaps with every simulation
 particle.
 The fraction of test particles without overlaps was recorded as the value
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $AVF\left(h_{i},\theta_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Multiple replicates with different random displacements from the grid were
 performed for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 The analysis was performed with 50 and 500 replicates, and 50 replicates
 were found to be sufficient to determine the AVF.
 The results from multiple runs of the Brownian dynamics simulation were
 averaged to obtain an estimate of the available volume function.
 The coefficients of the generalized diffusion equation were computed directly
 from the available volume function:
\begin_inset Formula \[
k_{1}=\frac{\partial}{\partial h}\log\gamma=\frac{-1}{AVF}\,\frac{\partial AVF}{\partial h}\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[
