\begin_layout Subsection
Implementation of the Continuum Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The control volume formulation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Patankar1980"

\end_inset

 was used to obtain a finite difference form of Equation 15 in the region
 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq h<2$
\end_inset

.
 Central differencing was used to approximate first derivatives in space,
 and a fully implicit scheme was used to approximate time derivatives.
 To ensure stability, the source term was linearized so that it was independent
 of the value of n.
 Any particle that touches the surfaces adsorbs, so the number density of
 particles at the surface is zero.
 The Dirichlet (type 1) boundary condition 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset

 was used at 
\begin_inset Formula $h=0$
\end_inset

.
 For simulations with constant near-surface concentration the type 1 boundary
 condition 
\begin_inset Formula $n=n_{b}$
\end_inset

 was applied at 
\begin_inset Formula $h=2$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Coupling the Continuum Model of Hard-Sphere Adsorption to a Conventional
 CFD Transport Simulation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For simulations in which the concentration at 
\begin_inset Formula $h=2$
\end_inset

 was influenced by diffusion, a second simulation domain was created to
 model diffusion in the bulk for 
\begin_inset Formula $h\geq2$
\end_inset

.
 The classical diffusion equation was discretized and solved in the bulk
 domain in the same manner as the generalized diffusion equation.
 The generalized diffusion equation was solved in the interaction region
 to obtain the net flux, using the value of number density at 
\begin_inset Formula $h=2$
\end_inset

 from the previous time step.
 For small values of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 the surface is mostly available for adsorption, so the net flux is limited
 by diffusive transport.
 The net flux is determined by 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{c}$
\end_inset

 rather than 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 Once the surface is mostly blocked, the net flux is determined by the rate
 at which particles can find available space on the surface, so the value
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{s}$
\end_inset

 should be used for the net flux.
 The correct value for the net flux can be computed by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
J\left(h=2,t\right)=-min\left(\left|J_{s}\right|,\left|J_{c}\right|\right)\label{eq:Net flux}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 The net flux from the generalized diffusion equation was used as the left-hand
 boundary condition to solve the classical diffusion equation in the bulk,
 which resulted in a new value for the number density at the interface.
 This number density was used to solve the generalized diffusion equation
 in the near-surface domain again, and the iterative process was repeated
 until the number density at the interface computed in each domain converged:
\begin_inset Formula $\left|n\left(h=2^{-}\right)-n\left(h=2^{+}\right)\right|<\delta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

